Lecture 15 | Predicting Non-Binary Outcomes Using Linear Regression

Today’s Question

In the linear model \(\hat{Y} = \hat{\alpha} + \hat{\beta}X\), the intercept coefficient, \(\hat{\alpha}\), can be interpreted as:

  1. the predicted Y when X=0
  2. the expected change in the predicted Y when X=0
  3. the predicted Y when X increases by one
  4. the expected change in the predicted Y when X increases by one

Plan for Today

  • Prediction and Linear Regression
  • Example with Non-binary Outcome Variable: Using Midterm Scores to Predict Final Exam Scores
  1. Load and explore data
  2. Identify X and Y
  3. What is the relationship between X and Y? (scatter plot and correlations)
  4. Fit a linear model using the least squares method 5. Interpret coefficients
  5. Make predictions

Using Midterm Scores to Predict Final Exam Scores

  • Today we will analyze student performance data

  • Our goal is to model the relationship between midterm and final exam scores

  • So that we can later predict final exam scores based on midterm scores

1. Load and explore data

data <- read.csv("grades.csv")

head(data)
##   midterm final overall gradeA
## 1   79.25 47.00    69.2      0
## 2   96.25 87.75    94.3      1
## 3   58.25 37.75    62.0      0
## 4   54.50 62.00    72.4      0
## 5   83.00 39.75    72.4      0
## 6   41.75 49.50    59.5      0
  • What’s the unit of observation?

2. Identify X and Y

  • The predictor (X) is the variable we want to use to predict the outcome (Y)
    • In this case, the predictor is midterm
    • Let’s visualize the distribution of midterm
ggplot(data = data) +
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = midterm), bins = 6)

  • The outcome (Y) is the variable that we want to predict
    • In this case, the outcome variable is final
    • Let’s visualize the distribution of final
ggplot(data = data) +
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = final), bins = 8)

3. What is the relationship between X and Y?

  • Create scatter plot to visualize the relationship between midterm and final
ggplot(data = data) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = midterm, y = final))

  • What does each dot represent?

  • Does the relationship look positive or negative?

  • Does the relationship look weekly or strongly linear?

  • Calculate correlation to measure direction and strength of linear association between midterm and final
cor(data$midterm, data$final)
## [1] 0.7160323

  • We find a moderately strong positive correlation

  • Are we surprised by this number?

  • Based on the scatter plot and the correlation between midterm and final we learn that an increase in midterm scores is associated with an increase in final scores

  • What we want to know is: when midterm scores increase, by how much are final scores predicted to increase?

  • In general we care about: when X increases by one unit, by how much is Y predicted to change?

  • To answer this question, we will fit a line to summarize the relationship between X and Y

4. Fit a linear model using the least squares method

  • Which line better summarizes the relationship?

  • The goal is the choose the line that best fits the data
    • Pick the line closest to the data
    • Which has the smallest prediction errors (vertical distance between dots and the line)?

  • To choose the line that best fits the data, we use the least squares method:
    • Chooses the line that minimizes prediction errors
    • In particular, it minimizes \(\sum_{i=1}^n\) \(\hat{\varepsilon}^2\)
      • Which is the sum of the squared of the prediction errors / residuals

  • A line is defined by two coefficients:
    • Intercept specifies the vertical location of the line
    • Slope specifies the angle or steepness of the line
  • Mathematically: the fitted line is \(\hat{Y} = \hat{\alpha} + \hat{\beta}X\)
    • \(\alpha\) is the intercept
    • \(\beta\) is the slope
  • If you learned that a line was \(Y = mX + b\)
    • Think that m is now \(\hat{\beta}\)
    • Think that b is now \(\hat{\alpha}\)
  • \(\hat{}\) (called “hat”) stands for predicted or estimated
    • \(\hat{Y}\) is the predicted outcome
    • \(\hat{\alpha}\) and \(\hat{\beta}\) are the estimated coefficients

  • R function to fit a linear model: lm()
    • Required argument: a formula of the type Y ~ X
lm(final ~ midterm, data = data)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = final ~ midterm, data = data)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)      midterm  
##     -6.0059       0.9704

  • \(\hat{\alpha}\) = -6.01 and \(\hat{\beta}\) = 0.97

  • The fitted line is \(\hat{Y} = -6.01 + 0.97X\)

  • More specifically: \(\hat{final} = -6.01 + 0.97midterm\)

  • We can now add the fitted line to the scatter plot above

  • First, we store the fitted line in an object called fit

fit <- lm(final ~ midterm, data = data)
  • Then, we can use the function abline() or geom_smooth()
    • Require argument: name of object with fitted line
#tidyverse
ggplot(data = data, mapping = aes(x = midterm, y = final)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

#base R
plot(data$midterm, data$final)
abline(fit, color = "blue")
## Warning in int_abline(a = a, b = b, h = h, v = v, untf = untf, ...): "color" is
## not a graphical parameter

5. Interpretation of Coefficients:

  • The intercept (\(\hat{\alpha}\)) is the \(\hat{Y}\) when X = 0

  • Find 0 on the X-axis, go up to the line, find the value of \(\hat{Y}\) associated with X=0

  • Here: \(\hat{\alpha}\) = -6.01

Mathematical Definition of \(\hat{\alpha}\)

  • Substantive interpretation of \(\hat{\alpha}\)

    • When a student scores 0 points in the midterm, we predict that in the final exam they will score -6.01 points, on average

  • Sometimes it is nonsensical (due to extrapolation)

  • Unit of measurement of \(\hat{\alpha}\)

    • Same as \(\bar{Y}\)
    • In this case, Y is non-binary and measured in points, so \(\bar{Y}\) is measured in points and so is \(\hat{\alpha}\)

  • The slope (\(\hat{\beta}\)) is the \(\bigtriangleup \hat{Y}\) associated with \(\bigtriangleup X = 1\)

  • Pick two points on the line, measure \(\bigtriangleup \hat{Y}\) and \(\bigtriangleup X\) associated with the two points, then calculate \(\bigtriangleup \hat{Y}\) | \(\bigtriangleup X\)

  • Here: \(\hat{\beta}\) = \(\frac{rise}{run}\) = \(\frac{71.6 - (-6.01)}{80 - 0}\) = \(\frac{77.61}{80}\) = 0.97
\(\bigtriangleup \hat{Y} = \hat{Y}final - \hat{Y}initial\)
\(\bigtriangleup X = Xfinal - Xinitial\)

Mathematical Definition of \(\hat{\beta}\)

  • Substantive interpretation of \(\hat{\beta}\)
    • \(\hat{\beta}\) is the \(\bigtriangleup \hat{Y}\) associated with a\(\bigtriangleup \hat{X}\) = 1
    • An increase in midterm scores of 1 point is associated with a predicted increase in final exam scores of 0.97 points, on average
    • Has the same sign as the cor(x,y) (always the case)
  • Unit of measurement of \(\hat{\beta}\)
    • Same as \(\bigtriangleup \bar{Y}\)
    • In this case, Y is non-binary and measured in points so \(\bigtriangleup \bar{Y}\) is measure in points and so is \(\hat{\beta}\)

  • The Fitted Line Is

\(\hat{Y} = \hat{\alpha} + \hat{\beta}X\)

  • \(\hat{\alpha}\) (alpha-hat) is the estimated intercept coefficient the \(\hat{Y}\) when X = 0

  • \(\hat{\beta}\) (beta-hat) is the estimated intercept coefficient the \(\bigtriangleup \bar{Y}\) when \(\bigtriangleup \bar{X}\) = 1

6. Make Predictions

  • Now that we have found the line that best summarizes the relationship between X and Y, we can use it to make predictions

  • There are two types of predictions that we might be interested in

    • Predict \(\hat{Y}\) based on X: \(\hat{Y} = \hat{\alpha} + \hat{\beta}X\)
    • Predict \(\bigtriangleup \hat{Y}\) associated with \(\bigtriangleup X\): \(\bigtriangleup \hat{Y}\) = \(\hat{\beta}\bigtriangleup X\)

  • To predict \(\hat{Y}\) based on X: \(\hat{Y} = \hat{\alpha} + \hat{\beta}X\)

  • Example 1: Imagine you earn 80 points in the midterm, what would we predict your final exam score will be?

\(\hat{final} = -6.01 + 0.97midterm\)
\(\hat{final} = -6.01 + 0.97 \times 80\) (if midterm = 80)
\(\hat{final} = 71.59\)

  • Therefore, if you earn 80 points in the midterm, we would predict that you will earn 71.59 points in the final exam, on average

  • Note: \(\hat{Y}\) is the same unit of measurement as \(\bar{Y}\)

    • In this case, Y is non-binary and measure in points so \(\bar{Y}\) and \(\hat{Y}\) are also measured in points

  • Example 2: Imagine you earn 90 points in the midterm, what would we predict your final exam score will be?
\(\hat{final} = -6.01 + 0.97midterm\)
\(\hat{final} = -6.01 + 0.97 \times 90\) (if midterm = 90)
\(\hat{final} = 81.29\)
  • Therefore, if you earn 90 points in the midterm, we would predict that you will earn 81.29 points in the final exam, on average

  • To predict \(\bigtriangleup \hat{Y}\) associated with \(\bigtriangleup X\): \(\bigtriangleup \hat{Y}\) = \(\hat{\beta}\bigtriangleup X\)

  • Example 3: If you increase your midterm scores by 10 points, by how much would we predict that your final exam scores would change?

\(\bigtriangleup\hat{final} = 0.97\bigtriangleup midterm\)
\(\bigtriangleup\hat{final} = 0.97 \times 10\) (if \(\bigtriangleup\) midterm = 10)
\(\bigtriangleup\hat{final} = 9.7\)
  • Therefore, an increase of midterm scores of 10 points is associated with a predicted increase of final exam scores of 9.7 points, on average
